06408nam a22008295i 9780824856090DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192020hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248560907 a10.1515/97808248560902doi  a(DE-B1597)518497  a(OCoLC)1125107978  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aN7315b.L9 2020eb 7aPOL0610002bisacsh04a700.95962231 aLy, Boreth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTraces of Trauma :bCambodian Visual Culture and National Identity in the Aftermath of Genocide /cBoreth Ly; ed. by David P. Chandler, Rita Smith Kipp. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (190 p.) :b29 color, 7 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory ;v6600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Broken Body: Situating Trauma in the Visual Cultures of Cambodia and Its Diaspora -- t2. Scarred Resilience: The Legacy of the United States’ Secret Bombing of Cambodia -- t3. Portraits of a Dictator: Khmer Rouge Ideology and the Politics of Aesthetics -- t4. Of Krama and Khmer Identity: The Land Where the Sugar Palm Trees Grow -- t5. Performing Khmer Cultural Identity: The Tale/Tail of the Serpent Princess -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do the people of a morally shattered culture and nation find ways to go on living? Cambodians confronted this challenge following the collective disasters of the American bombing, the civil war, and the Khmer Rouge genocide. The magnitude of violence and human loss, the execution of artists and intellectuals, the erasure of individual and institutional cultural memory all caused great damage to Cambodian arts, culture, and society. Author Boreth Ly explores the “traces” of this haunting past in order to understand how Cambodians at home and in the diasporas deal with trauma on such a vast scale.Ly maintains that the production of visual culture by contemporary Cambodian artists and writers—photographers, filmmakers, court dancers, and poets—embodies traces of trauma, scars leaving an indelible mark on the body and the psyche. His book considers artists of different generations and family experiences: a Cambodian-American woman whose father sent her as a baby to the United States to be adopted; the Cambodian-French film-maker, Rithy Panh, himself a survivor of the Khmer Rouge, whose film The Missing Picture was nominated for an Oscar in 2014; a young Cambodian artist born in 1988—part of the “post-memory” generation. The works discussed include a variety of materials and remnants from the historical past: the broken pieces of a shattered clay pot, the scarred landscape of bomb craters, the traditional symbolism of the checkered scarf called krama, as well as the absence of a visual archive.Boreth Ly’s poignant book explores obdurate traces that are fragmented and partial, like the acts of remembering and forgetting. His interdisciplinary approach, combining art history, visual studies, psychoanalysis, cultural studies, religion, and philosophy, is particularly attuned to the diverse body of material discussed in his book, which includes photographs, video installations, performance art, poetry, and mixed media. By analyzing these works through the lens of trauma, he shows how expressions of a national trauma can contribute to healing and the reclamation of national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArts, Cambodian. 0aGenocidezCambodiaxPsychological aspects. 0aNationalism and the artszCambodia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Genocide & War Crimes.2b